        <div id="readable-content">
        <!-- Pedestrians -->
        <div id="pedestrians" class="guide-card">
            <h3><span>🚶</span> For Pedestrians</h3>
            <p>Pedestrians are among the most vulnerable road users. Big or small, fast or slow — every road user needs to do their part to stay safe.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Always cross at designated crossings</strong> — zebra crossings, overhead bridges, underpasses or signalised junctions. Avoid jaywalking, even if it looks like a shortcut.</li>
                <li><strong>Look both ways</strong> before crossing, and keep checking as you cross. Never assume a driver has seen you.</li>
                <li><strong>Put your phone away</strong> while crossing. Distracted crossing is one of the everyday lapses that traffic police repeatedly flag as a factor in accidents.</li>
                <li><strong>Be visible at night</strong> — wear light-coloured or reflective clothing, especially near roads without good street lighting.</li>
                <li><strong>Watch out for turning vehicles</strong> at junctions, even when the pedestrian light is green — drivers making turns don't always see pedestrians stepping off the kerb.</li>
                <li><strong>Be extra careful around the elderly</strong> — seniors made up a disproportionate share of pedestrian deaths in 2025, and giving way and slowing down protects them.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="source-note">Source: Singapore Police Force, Road Safety Tips for Pedestrians</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Cyclists / PMD -->
        <div id="cyclists" class="guide-card">
            <h3><span>🚲</span> For Cyclists & PMD Riders</h3>
            <p>Cycling and personal mobility devices (PMDs) are increasingly common ways to get around Singapore — but they come with rules that exist for good reason.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Helmets are compulsory</strong> when cycling or riding a power-assisted bicycle (PAB) on the road. Wear elbow and knee pads too if you can — they cushion falls.</li>
                <li><strong>Ring your bell</strong> to give pedestrians advance warning as you approach them on shared paths.</li>
                <li><strong>Wear light-coloured or reflective clothing</strong> to boost your visibility to other road users, especially at night.</li>
                <li><strong>No phones while riding</strong> — since August 2020, it's an offence to hold a mobile device and use its functions while riding a bicycle or PAB.</li>
                <li><strong>PMDs must be LTA-approved</strong> with a valid seal, registered and number-plated — and riders must be at least 16 years old. Pillion riders must also be 16 or older.</li>
                <li><strong>PMDs are banned from footpaths</strong> — they can only be used on cycling paths, park connectors, and where explicitly allowed. This rule exists because PMD-related injuries on footpaths dropped by over half once the ban took effect.</li>
                <li><strong>Slow down near pedestrians</strong> and give way — a fall at even 15km/h can cause serious head injuries.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="source-note">Source: SPF Road Safety Tips for Cyclists; LTA Road Safety Guide</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Passengers -->
        <div id="passengers" class="guide-card">
            <h3><span>🚗</span> For Passengers</h3>
            <p>Being a good passenger is a road safety skill too — and it's one every young person in Singapore practises daily on buses, in cars, and on the MRT.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Always buckle up</strong>, front seat or back — seatbelts are the single most effective protection in a collision.</li>
                <li><strong>Don't distract the driver</strong> — loud noise, sudden movements or arguments can pull a driver's attention off the road at the worst possible moment.</li>
                <li><strong>Speak up if a driver is unsafe</strong> — whether that's a friend driving too fast, using a phone, or driving after drinking. It's not rude to ask them to slow down or pull over.</li>
                <li><strong>Board and alight safely</strong> from buses and cars — wait until vehicles have fully stopped, and check for oncoming traffic and cyclists before opening a car door.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- New drivers / learners -->
        <div id="new-drivers" class="guide-card">
            <h3><span>🪪</span> For Future & New Drivers</h3>
            <p>Many secondary school and JC students in Singapore start thinking about driving lessons early. Here's what to know before you're behind the wheel.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>The Highway Code matters</strong> — the Basic Theory of Driving handbook covers the traffic rules, signs and signals every licensed road user is legally expected to know.</li>
                <li><strong>New drivers are on probation</strong> for one year after getting their licence, and must display a probation plate. Racking up 13 or more demerit points during this period revokes the licence.</li>
                <li><strong>Speeding is a leading cause of serious accidents</strong> — the faster you drive, the less time you have to react. Speeding violations surged in 2025 even as enforcement intensified.</li>
                <li><strong>Never drink and drive.</strong> Singapore is lowering its legal blood-alcohol limit, and drink-driving remains one of the most dangerous and heavily enforced offences on the road.</li>
                <li><strong>Keep a lookout for vulnerable road users</strong> — cyclists, PMD riders, children and the elderly may not always predictably follow the rules, so defensive driving matters.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="source-note">Source: SPF Basic Theory of Driving handbook; Ministry of Home Affairs road safety announcements (2026)</p>
        </div>
        </div><!-- /#readable-content -->

